<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-512-146  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 512 146.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FRAM chips enter the memory menagerie. (ferroelectric RAM chips)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ferroelectronic RAM (FRAM) chips, which combine conventionalsemiconductor materials with ferroelectronic ceramics to increaseefficiency, will be available in computing devices by 1992.andP;  FRAMscan contain more capacitors per circuit than other chips andretain data for up to 10 years without power Ramtron Corp anNational Semiconductor Corp have developed a new way of producingFRAMs by applying a film of ferroelectronic material to asemiconductor wafer to product true non-volatile RAM.andP;  A FRAMcould store enough data to replace DIP switches in manyperipherals.andP;  Several US, Japanese and European firms are racingto develop FRAM technology.andP;  Ramtron will open a production plantin Colorado Springs in 1990 and plans to manufacture 1K-bit to16K-bit FRAMs immediately, with 256K-bit chips in production by1991.andP;  Proponents of FRAM technology say that the new chips couldrevolutionize the computer business.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ramtron International Corp. (innovations).andO;Topic:     New TechniqueRAMCircuit DesignNonvolatile Memory.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>